We are currently experiencing a persistent issue where no DAGs can be run in ochre-1-dead-dev-1 due to the Airflow scheduler becoming overloaded. 
Per Ventsi's investigation, the scheduler is being overwhelmed during DAG promotion. The overload is triggered by a custom function (forceDagReload()) defined in airflowFunctions.groovy, which explicitly forces a full DAG reserialization across all DAGs. When hundreds of DAGs are present, this causes excessive load on the scheduler, ultimately preventing any DAGs from running and requiring a manual pod restart to resolve.
This issue was previously masked due to Kraken pod eviction happening during the same time window (12–2pm), which implicitly restarted the scheduler and allowed things to self-heal. Now that Kraken runs overnight, the scheduler remains stuck and requires manual intervention.
• All DAGs blocked from running.

• Airflow UI stuck at the cluster creation stage.

• Scheduler logs show the following recurring error:
Error sending Celery task: module 'redis' has no attribute 'client'Actions Required:
• Remove or disable the forceDagReload() function from airflowFunctions.groovy, which currently runs:
def forceDagReload() {
    def podName = getPodName()
    def airflowNamespace = "airflow2"
    def execPrefix = "kubectl exec -n ${airflowNamespace} ${podName} --"
    def command = "${execPrefix} airflow dags reserialize > /dev/null 2>&1 || true"
    def result = sh(script: command, returnStatus: true)

    if (result != 0) {
        println "Warning: Airflow DAG reserialization encountered errors but will proceed."
    } else {
        println "Successfully forced Airflow to reload DAGs."
    }
}
• Replace with passive DAG pickup strategy — allow Airflow to detect new DAGs naturally without forcing reserialization.
