After doing everything imaginable like adding TimeZone.setDefault(TimeZone.getTimeZone("Etc/UTC")) in the code in many places, the dates are still off by a day, and it's unclear why (see my hail mary attempt here on the BVD_JENKINS_TIMEZONE branch). The anomaly seems to be related to the Fusion functions parseDateParts and parseDateString exhibiting strange behavior in the DocumentIndexInput, as seen here:
"appointmentDate": {
    "dateRaw": "2014-07-08",
    "dateParts": {
      "date": "2014-07-07",
      "year": "2014",
      "month": "07",
      "day": "08"
    }
  },Observe the mismatch between dateRaw,dateParts.date, and dateParts.day. This is from the JSON that is produced locally after manually setting the timezone as above. It comes from the CleanseBvdDate object which converts RawBvdDate to BvdDate containing date parts. This isn't the issue that we're seeing on Jenkins, but it is   seems that the java.sql.Date class in the ParsedDateParts case class is a part of the problem. This class, governed by the default time zone settings of the JVM in the Scala environment, does not retain time zone information, potentially causing the date to shift by a day based on the original time zone of the date string.Even after setting the timezone manually as above which I've done for other data-packs (e.g., Grid or Dowjones), it seems like something, possibly within the Fusion functions, overrides this setting.If we can't fix this from our own code, we may have to contact Fusion team to find a solution that ensures consistency in the dateRaw, dateParts.date, and dateParts.day fields in the JSON output.
